[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/blackwood"]
[Student "S"]
{Your 1NT bid showed 15-17 points and a balanced hand. Decide how you would answer partner's Gerber 4\C, then click on <b>BID</b> above. 

The Gerber response to show 2 Aces is 4\S. So you bid 4\S and partner jumps to 6NT, which you pass.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "S:AQJ.QJT5.975.KQJ 97532.864.A.9642 K8.K2.KQJT843.A3 T64.A973.62.T875"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "4NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1NT pass 4C pass 4H pass 4NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: S, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:2, nBasis: 0, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/blackwood"]
[Student "S"]
{Very interesting! If partner's 1NT bid happens to include 3 Aces and one King you can count 13 tricks! So you bid 4\C, definitely Gerber following the 1NT opening. Partner answers 4\H. What do you say next? 

You almost refuse to believe it! How can partner have a 1NT opener with only 1 Ace? But you trust your partner so you bid 4NT. Everybody passes and you stare in amazement at partner's 16 points.

Wouldn't it have been funny if partner had thought your 4\C bid was Stayman? And so his 4\H bid would have been showing a suit. And then your 4NT bid would have been Blackwood. And then he would have answered 5\D and you would have passed and made it!}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "S:5432.984.A75.875 A98.KQJT.KJ6.AQ3 JT6.732.942.T962 KQ7.A65.QT83.KJ4"]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "6NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
pass 2NT pass 4C pass 4S pass 6NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: W, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:3, nBasis: 2, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/blackwood"]
[Student "S"]
{With a 20 point balanced hand you open 2NT. What do you rebid after partner jumps to 4\C? 

The 4\C bid is Gerber and your correct response with 2 Aces is 4\S. Partner now bids 6NT and since he is the Captain you pass.}

